            "theory": "**Shallow vs Deep copy:**\n- `b = a` — both variables reference the **same** list\n- `b = a.copy()` or `b = a[:]` — creates a **shallow copy** (nested objects still shared)\n- `import copy; b = copy.deepcopy(a)` — creates a fully independent copy\n\n**Memory:** A Python list is a dynamic array of object pointers. Appending is O(1) amortized; inserting at position 0 is O(n).\n\n**`*` unpacking in lists:**\n`a, *b, c = [1,2,3,4,5]  # a=1, b=[2,3,4], c=5`\n\n**`list.__slots__` doesn't exist** — lists use dynamic arrays internally. For huge sequences of homogeneous numbers, prefer `array.array` or `numpy.ndarray` for memory efficiency.",
